[
    {
        "content": "<p>Categorical semantics of linear logic commonly takes place in LNL adjunctions. Mellies' book expounds this but seem to not dwell much on the closed structure. Does anyone have a good reference where this is expounded in greater detail?</p>",
        "id": 532320350,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754059079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The following notes by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276656\">@Valeria de Paiva</span> seem a good place to start! I didn't know that categorical semantics of linear logic could be so subtle:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://vcvpaiva.github.io/includes/pubs/catsem4all.pdf\">https://vcvpaiva.github.io/includes/pubs/catsem4all.pdf</a></p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 532330578,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754062414
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for this  <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> !</p>",
        "id": 532331654,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754062758
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You might be interested in my paper on <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.15042\">LNL polycategories</a>.  Closed structures are discussed in section 2 as an instance of a general notion of universal morphism that also includes products and modalities, but I didn't dwell on them much either.  I'm not sure that there's much to say by dwelling on them -- did you have specific questions?</p>",
        "id": 532343505,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1754066996
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What does LNL stand for?   <span aria-label=\"cry\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f622\" role=\"img\" title=\"cry\">:cry:</span></p>",
        "id": 532343880,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1754067055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Linear Non Linear</p>",
        "id": 532343955,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754067076
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nick Benton's categorical model for linear logic, ie. a monoidal adjunction</p>",
        "id": 532344102,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754067130
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I write \"Linear-NonLinear\" to emphasize the parsing -- an adjunction or other structure that relates a category of Linear objects to a category of NonLinear objects.</p>",
        "id": 532344217,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1754067176
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My point about LNL models is that they're much easier to state, but end up being as difficult to check as Linear Categories, the old model.</p>",
        "id": 532344590,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754067310
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"adjunctions\" are a really clever encapsulation of lots of things</p>",
        "id": 532344752,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754067373
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/closed.20structure.20in.20LNL.20adjunctions/near/532343505\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You might be interested in my paper on <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.15042\">LNL polycategories</a>.  Closed structures are discussed in section 2 as an instance of a general notion of universal morphism that also includes products and modalities, but I didn't dwell on them much either.  I'm not sure that there's much to say by dwelling on them -- did you have specific questions?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thanks Mike, I read your paper a while ago and I should revisit it with new eyes.</p>\n<p>My specific question is understandimg what exactly <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo>⊸</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{!\\multimap} = {\\to}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.3669em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span></span> means, from a categorical standpoint. From Valeria's notes it seems that, given a symmetric monoidal closed category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> involved in a symmetric monoidal adjunction with a cartesian category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, the latter automatically gains a cartesian closed structure, which I guess is given by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊸</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!(A \\multimap B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span></span></span> is the right adjoint going <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. This is allegedly discussed by Barber, Benton and Plotkin but I can't find the relevant paper.<br>\nThe reason I'm confused is that reading logic papers, I'm lead to believe the intuitionistic arrow <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.3669em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> is defined for every type rather than just the 'non-linear' ones in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> (and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> can be comparatively smaller than <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>, as in the example I care about). So perhaps I'm missing something glaringly obvious (I'm no stranger to such blunders...). <br>\nThis perhaps would help me better conceptualise the relationship between BI and LL...</p>",
        "id": 532537654,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754213079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span>  here is the reference  for Barber's thesis <a href=\"https://www.lfcs.inf.ed.ac.uk/reports/96/ECS-LFCS-96-347/\">https://www.lfcs.inf.ed.ac.uk/reports/96/ECS-LFCS-96-347/</a><br>\nBut you got it slightly mangled: \"given a symmetric monoidal closed category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> involved in a symmetric monoidal adjunction with a cartesian category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, the latter automatically gains a cartesian closed structure\",  is ok. But this is not given by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊸</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!(A \\multimap B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. the intuitionistic arrow <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.3669em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> is indeed defined for every pair of types  in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 532559828,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754229663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Valeria! How is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.3669em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> defined then?</p>",
        "id": 532561247,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754230485
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the reference you give the cartesian category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is assumed closed already</p>",
        "id": 532561277,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754230509
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span>  I will confess that I'm a bit rusty on this, but in page 11 of <br>\n<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?&amp;q=A.%20Barber%20and%20G.%20Plotkin%3A%20Dual%20intuitionistic%20linear%20logic.%20Submitted%20%281998%29\">https://scholar.google.com/scholar?&amp;q=A.%20Barber%20and%20G.%20Plotkin%3A%20Dual%20intuitionistic%20linear%20logic.%20Submitted%20%281998%29</a><br>\nwhich was the original version of the thesis, one finds  section \"3.5 A Definable Intuitionistic Function Space\" where Barber defines the internal-hom following Girard's original def as <br>\nA-&gt;B:= !A -o B, using a term construction, via multicategories. This might not be enough for your purposes.</p>",
        "id": 532571476,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754236485
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Typically, for objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X, Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, the cartesian closed structure is defined by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊸</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(!X) \\multimap Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>. I'm a little confused by what's written above, because it doesn't seem to type-check: you can't apply a functor to an entire category.</p>",
        "id": 532576034,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1754239130
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm using A and B as objects of the linear category.</p>",
        "id": 532587529,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1754246903
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry, I meant what Matteo had written.</p>",
        "id": 532589716,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1754248443
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>First: in the general LNL case with two classes of objects, I prefer to reserve <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span></span></span> for the induced comonad on the category of linear objects, which decomposes as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi stretchy=\"false\">!</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathord{!} = \\mathsf{F} \\mathsf{U}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">FU</span></span></span></span> for the adjunction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{F} \\dashv \\mathsf{U}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">U</span></span></span></span> between the nonlinear and linear categories.</p>\n<p>Second: in this general situation, I don't see how one can deduce a closed structure on the entire cartesian category of nonlinear objects from having one on the monoidal category of linear objects.  I can only see how to define the cartesian hom <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\mathsf{U}B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a nonlinear object and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is a linear object, the definition being <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>⊸</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(X \\to \\mathsf{U}B) = \\mathsf{U}(\\mathsf{F}X \\multimap B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">U</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I believe the traditional setup, with only one class of objects, is best encoded in the general LNL context by taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{U}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">U</span></span></span></span> to be the identity on objects.  In this case, the action of the comonad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span></span></span> on objects coincides with that of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">F</span></span></span></span>, and so the above definition simplifies to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>⊸</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(X\\to B) = (!X \\multimap B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.  However, I find it less confusing to think about the general case, with two distinct categories each with their own objects.</p>",
        "id": 532593026,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1754250747
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/closed.20structure.20in.20LNL.20adjunctions/near/532576034\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Typically, for objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X, Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, the cartesian closed structure is defined by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊸</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(!X) \\multimap Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>. I'm a little confused by what's written above, because it doesn't seem to type-check: you can't apply a functor to an entire category.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I messed up notation, I also meant A and B as objects in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊸</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!A \\multimap B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>!</p>",
        "id": 532663489,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754292543
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/closed.20structure.20in.20LNL.20adjunctions/near/532593026\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I believe the traditional setup, with only one class of objects, is best encoded in the general LNL context by taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{U}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">U</span></span></span></span> to be the identity on objects. In this case, the action of the comonad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span></span></span> on objects coincides with that of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">F</span></span></span></span>, and so the above definition simplifies to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>⊸</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(X\\to B) = (!X \\multimap B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊸</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Indeed, this seems what logicians implicitly assume, but then I have never seen this mentioned explicitly in the categorical semantics (only exception being Seely categories where the adjunction is coKleisli, hence the right adjoint is ioo)...</p>",
        "id": 532664745,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1754292981
    }
]